net
Class Example

java.lang.Object
  net.Example
All Implemented Interfaces:
Network_iface
public class Example
extends java.lang.Object
implements Network_iface

This is a very simple example showing the most basic use of Network and Network_iface. Feel free to use, overwrite, or just ignore code as you like. As a default, a connection speed of 115200 baud is assumed. You can use a different speed by giving it as an int as the first command line argument or changing the default speed in the source code.

Author:
Raphael Blatter (raphael@blatter.sg)

parseInput

public void parseInput(int id,
                       int numBytes,
                       int[] message)
Implementing Network_iface.parseInput(int, int, int[]) to handle messages received over the serial port. In this example, the received bytes are written to command line (0 to 254) and the message is sent back over the same serial port.

Specified by:
parseInput in interface Network_iface
Parameters:
id - The int passed to Network.Network(int, Network_iface, int) in the constructor. It can be used to identify which instance a message comes from, when several instances of Network are connected to the same instance of a class implementing this interface.
numBytes - Number of valid bytes contained in the message
message - Message received over the Serial interface. The complete array of bytes (as ints between 0 and 255) between Network.divider is sent (without Network.dividers).
See Also:
Network_iface

writeLog

public void writeLog(int id,
                     java.lang.String text)
Implementing Network_iface.writeLog(int, String), which is used to write information concerning the connection. In this example, all the information is simply written out to command line.

Specified by:
writeLog in interface Network_iface
Parameters:
id - The int passed to Network.Network(int, Network_iface, int) in the constructor. It can be used to identify which instance (which connection) a message comes from, when several instances of Network are connected to the same instance of a class implementing this interface.
text - The text to be written into the log in human readable form. Corresponds to information about the connection or ports.
See Also:
